Negotiation and Compromise are the Important Means of Democracy ! (ZT) 
Houze 
I just now saw a poster on " Great Decency - To Old Mr. Guiren " sent by a network friend . 
His ( her ) original words are that " Negotiation and compromise are the important means of democracy . Otherwise , a split because of different views is a failure of democracy ! ! ! Hope that those ideal democrats pay fully attention to this ! " 
This plain and tasteless sentence , which has not attracted interest from any network friends , has made me imagine a lot and have many sorts of feelings . 
At that moment I thought of the ancient times of China and the past of the West . 
I seldom sent the main poster . I cannot help but reply to the poster of the network friend in the way of the main poster . 
Let 's see China 's ancient times . 
Everyone knows that since Qin Shihuang established the universally unified and centralized power system in China , any subsequent dynasties were operated under the political framework . 
Although the Han Dynasty temporarily implemented a " two - track system , " i.e . a political system that practiced the feudal system and centralized power system at the same time , it eventually switched to a complete centralized power system in the end . 
The outcome of this kind of centralized power system had an advanced aspect in the historical condition by then , which promoted the development of productivity . 
But we should also see that the long - term operation of the system for more than 2,000 years had made local administrations lacking of their creativities , initiatives , and enthusiasms , and unable to make various suitable systems and policies for local developments based on local circumstances . 
The pyramid type of ruling system had made lower - class officials looking upward only and following directions from their superiors for everything . 
There was no room for coordination and negotiation because even local officials at the county level were appointed by the central government , not to mention those common people . 
When rights of farmers were infringed upon in ancient China , they could only bear it time and again . 
Only when their basest rights were threatened , i.e . when a famine spread in big areas , a tyrannical rule or natural disaster caused loss of their living rights , would they rebel . 
In more than 2,000 years , many peasant uprisings spread everywhere in the country like storms , but they never won a victory in a real sense except Zhu Yuanzhang , from Chen Sheng , and Wu Guang , who did not plan their uprising to the planned Huang Jin Insurrection , from the Huang Chao Revolt in the Tang Dynasty to the Li Zhicheng Rebellion that established a dynasty for only a month . 
Even the Ming Dynasty created by Zhu Yuanzhang was only a cycle of other dynasties , and there were no systematic changes . 
Zhu Yuanzhang , who came from a common family and did not receive much education , played the Chinese ancient centralized power system to a sick extent , and to extremes . Since then , the vigorous state of the type of the Tang Dynasty that was open , free , and tolerant , had become depressed . 
The atmosphere of freedom of speech disappeared in the vast land of China for a time . 
Human nature was suppressed to the maximum extent . 
Everybody became very cautious and dared not to say more words with reverence and awe . 
This was the only outcome of peasant uprisings in 2,000 years , and it made Chinese people neither humans nor ghosts . 
Let 's see the Medieval Ages of the so - called dark time in Western Europe . 
The Medieval Ages of Western Europe were formed after the Western Rome was destroyed by nomadic nations , and lasted for a thousand years . They had nothing to do with the ancient Greece and Rome of the past . 
Those ages featured the feudal system , i.e . land holding . 
Many layers of land feudal lords , from the top to the bottom , had more autonomy . 
No matter whether small feudal lords who had an area of several square kilometers , or nobles who had titles of Duke , Marquis , Count , Viscount , and Baron , since superiors and inferiors , and the left and right , could balance , restrain , and were interdependent with each other , and had their prerequisites and capabilities to strive for their own rights against kings , the scenes in which nobles sat with a king negotiating for their own interest emerged , which never happened in China 's 
Compromises and concessions were made mutually instead use of violent means to knock down or replace opponents . 
In this way , through making various contracts , rights were continuously transferred to nobles and common people , and they had more and more rights , and kings had fewer and fewer . 
Later , the British Queen had only a status for display , and not any substantial power . 
Democracy was gradually realized in this way ! 
Let 's come back again to compare with ancient China , where every power was concentrated in the hands of emperors ( except Li Shimin ) , and there were almost no nobles . It was very difficult for peasants to be able to sit in front of a negotiation table , joyfully making compromises and concessions on a contract agreed to by both sides while enjoying a cup of tea or a glass of wine . 
Under this circumstance , when the living right was taken away , only violent means could overthrow an existing dynasty and try to replace it . 
Its outcome was the repeated cycle from the peak of the Tang Dynasty to the sick status of the Ming Dynasty . 
Comparing histories between China and the West , we discovered that the contradictions between rulers and the ruled in ancient China were much more intensified than those in ancient Western countries . 
No Western countries had so many continuous peasant uprisings as ancient China had . 
In the Western countries , when differences between ancient royal families and peasants emerged , what nobles and common people thought of first was to settle them through a negotiation path , to obtain more rights gradually by making mutual concessions , and they seldom used violent means . 
Understanding this , when we enter into the 21st century , we can still see those democratic warriors in networks who have inherited the ideology of the absolute power concentration system of the Ming Dynasty , 
and have been poisoned by the virus of the Cultural Revolution that they can say nothing except those words of " Down with or overthrow something . " 
And those concepts are the biggest barrier to democracy , because those people do not understand that negotiation , coordination , and compromise are the most important means and path for realization of democracy . 
Cao Xiaoming : Who is Going to " Pay the Bill " for Enriching Cultural Activities in Rural Areas 
Hou Ze 
The author was lucky to spend this year 's Spring Festival in a rural area of the Mainland , and visited some relatives and friends . 
I was not only influenced by the dense atmosphere of the festival in the Chinese rural area , but also concerned about those boring cultural activities there . 
The author discovered in a village where my relatives lived that this village organized villagers spontaneously to play a drama called " trotting horse lamp " for every Spring Festival in the past . 
The drama is based on figures in the story of The Three Kingdoms . Any adult or child could play a role in the drama , and villagers were not bored at all to watch it a hundred times . 
There were several of this kind of performance teams of " trotting horse lamp " in the whole township . They performed not only in their own villages , but also went to other villages for visits , and exchanged frequently . 
But this village did not organize the performance this year . 
The reason is that just the costumes for " trotting horse lamp " would cost a lot , which were bought in the past through donations from villagers . Now they are too worn out to be taken on . 
Nobody was willing to donate any more , if asking villagers for donations household by household . Other villages in the township had a similar situation . 
The village suddenly became quiet without the " trotting horse lamp . " 
Adults started to play Mahjong . 
Children also began to play cards . 
Villagers said that this festival had no fun . 
The big scene in the countryside is either shooting off fireworks or playing Mahjong during the festival . 
The gambling trend cannot be stopped even though it is prohibited time and again , and is spread even further . Gambling for up to ten thousand Yuan has become a routine game . Especially , big batches of those migrant farmer workers who come back to their hometowns from other areas have played major roles in gambling sites . 
Their hard - earned money from working in other areas for a year is lost in this way . 
Family disputes occurred time and again because of gambling , which sometimes causes tragedies with families broken up and decimated . 
Some farmers said that they gambled not only during festivals but also participated in gambling frequently in slack seasons . 
Nowhere to go if they did not gamble . 
It is too difficult to organize cultural activities and look for " fun " in the countryside . 
Not only are there no facilities and funding , but also nobody organizes them . 
But in this aspect , the practice in Jiangxi is definitely good news for farmers . 
To enrich the cultural life of the farmer masses , the government of Jiangxi Province not only implemented the policy that " the government provides funding for it ; the market operates it ; townships build stages ; and farmers watch dramas " last September , 
but they also arranged at least 60 million Yuan every year for the special fund for rural cultural causes and delivered good - quality cultural products to the rural masses . 
In the beginning of this New Year , it added an additional 40 million Yuan , a total of 100 million Yuan , for the establishment of special funding for the rural cultural cause . 
And also , what this special funding " paid " toward the farmers ' " bill " is quite a good deal : 
Various professional performance organizations are invited to have shows in rural areas , and provide at least four shows for every town each year . 
Movie companies at every level are invited to organize film projection teams to show movies in the countryside , and at least six feature or scientific education movies should be shown for every administrative village each year ; 
Cultural activities with local features participated in by the masses are organized and developed at least two to three times for every township each year . 
It is not difficult for us to see from the " purchase list " that the government does not simply pay the bill , but thinks hard how to use the limited funds in the critical area and deliver a cultural banquet that exceeds its money value to the farmer masses , and has done a big substantial thing for them . 
Now , a lot of farmers are very happy and joyful for immunity from providing " royal grains and state 's tax . " 
If every government can pay the " bill " for enriching cultural activities of the farmer masses as Jiangxi did , it would be another happy thing falling from the sky for farmers . 
And this " happy thing " can not only liberate farmers from the Mahjong table , and make them " active " in cultural activities , but also add bricks and tiles for the construction of the new socialist countryside . 
